    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think it might be the nitrogen though. how do i check if the soil pH is actually affecting how they take up nutrients? i don't want to just dump fertilizer if the soil is too acidic or something.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Checking your soil pH is a smart move, because if the pH is off, your tomatoes might be starving even if the nutrients are right there in the soil! You can get a simple home test kit from a garden center, or for more accuracy, send a soil sample to a local agricultural extension office. These kits will tell you if your soil is too acidic or too alkaline, which is crucial for nutrient uptake. If it's too acidic, you might need to add lime, and if it's too alkaline, sulfur can help bring it down.",
      "source": "target",
